{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Fresh debt and replacement borrowers bypass opening collateral-ratio checks","locations":["0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/actions/SellCreditMarket.sol:72","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/actions/SellCreditMarket.sol:231","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/actions/BuyCreditMarket.sol:71","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/actions/BuyCreditMarket.sol:231","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/actions/LiquidateWithReplacement.sol:48","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/actions/LiquidateWithReplacement.sol:148","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/RiskLibrary.sol:136"],"claim":"The protocol defines an opening-collateral safeguard in `RiskLibrary.validateUserIsNotBelowOpeningLimitBorrowCR`, but none of the debt-origination paths invoke it before minting debt and moving cash. `sellCreditMarket` with `creditPositionId == RESERVED_ID` mints debt for `onBehalfOf` and pays out lender cash without checking the borrower's live collateral ratio; `buyCreditMarket` does the same when matching a borrower offer; and `liquidateWithReplacement` reassigns the full debt to `params.borrower` and mints debt tokens for them without enforcing `crOpening` or the user's custom `openingLimitBorrowCR`.","impact":"Borrowers can open or receive new debt while below the protocol's required opening collateral ratio, including with zero effective collateral. This lets them extract fresh borrow-side value that is not economically recoverable, leaving lenders with bad debt and enabling replacement liquidations to convert an otherwise valid liquidation into a newly unsecured loan.","paths":["A borrower calls `sellCreditMarket` with `creditPositionId == RESERVED_ID`, receives cash from a lender's borrow aToken balance, and no opening-CR check runs before `createDebtAndCreditPositions` mints debt.","A lender calls `buyCreditMarket` against a borrower offer (`creditPositionId == RESERVED_ID`), opening debt for a borrower whose current collateral ratio is already below `crOpening` or their stricter user-defined opening limit.","A privileged caller uses `liquidateWithReplacement`; after the old borrower is liquidated, the same `futureValue` is reminted onto `params.borrower` even if that replacement borrower has insufficient or no collateral."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"ETH-backed deposits mint against the contractâ€™s full ETH balance instead of the callerâ€™s contribution","locations":["0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/actions/Deposit.sol:57","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/market/libraries/actions/Deposit.sol:92"],"claim":"For native-ETH deposits into the WETH-backed market path, `executeDeposit` ignores `params.amount` after validation and wraps `address(this).balance` instead. Any ETH already sitting on the market contract is therefore included in the amount deposited and credited to the current depositor.","impact":"Forced ETH, accidental direct transfers, or leftover ETH trapped on the market contract can be stolen by the next valid ETH depositor, who receives deposit credit for more ETH than they actually supplied.","paths":["ETH is forced or accidentally sent to the market contract outside the normal deposit flow.","An attacker later calls the WETH/native-ETH deposit path with a valid nonzero `msg.value`.","`executeDeposit` sets `amount = address(this).balance`, wraps the full balance, and mints the resulting deposit position to the attacker."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"User-chosen routers in `DexSwap` can drain residual balances from the shared zap contract","locations":["0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/src/liquidator/DexSwap.sol:156","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/src/liquidator/DexSwap.sol:216","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/src/zaps/LeverageUp.sol:49"],"claim":"`DexSwap` approves caller-specified routers to spend contract-held tokens and then executes arbitrary external calls without any router allowlist or post-swap balance invariant. Because `LeverageUp.leverageUpWithSwap` forwards attacker-controlled `swapParamsArray` into these helpers, any user can point the zap at a malicious router and have it pull whatever balance of the approved token the contract currently holds.","impact":"Any ERC20 left on the zap contract from dust, accidental transfers, partial routes, or future integrations can be stolen by arbitrary users. The unlimited approvals used by the generic-route path also enlarge the blast radius if a previously approved router later becomes malicious or compromised.","paths":["An attacker calls `leverageUpWithSwap` and supplies a `GenericRoute` or `BuyPt` step whose `router` they control.","`DexSwap` approves that router to spend the zap's current `tokenIn` balance and then performs the external call.","The malicious router uses the approval to transfer residual contract-held tokens out of the zap."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Oracle fails open to an unbounded Uniswap V3 TWAP whenever Chainlink pricing reverts","locations":["0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/oracle/v1.5.1/PriceFeed.sol:61","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/oracle/adapters/ChainlinkPriceFeed.sol:87","0xf4a21ac7e51d17a0e1c8b59f7a98bb7a97806f14/lib/size-solidity/src/oracle/adapters/UniswapV3PriceFeed.sol:77"],"claim":"`PriceFeed.getPrice()` catches any failure from the Chainlink path and immediately returns the Uniswap V3 TWAP instead. Since the fallback feed has no deviation check against the last trusted Chainlink price and no secondary sanity bounds, stale or reverting Chainlink rounds cause the protocol to trust a directly manipulable DEX-based price as the sole source of truth.","impact":"During Chainlink outages, stale updates, or other feed failures, an attacker who can move the Uniswap pool price over the configured TWAP window can distort collateral ratios used by borrowing and liquidation logic. That can enable wrongful liquidations or the creation/maintenance of undercollateralized debt at manipulated prices.","paths":["A Chainlink base or quote round becomes stale or otherwise causes `chainlinkPriceFeed.getPrice()` to revert.","`PriceFeed.getPrice()` falls back to `uniswapV3PriceFeed.getPrice()` with no bound against the last good Chainlink answer.","An attacker manipulates the referenced Uniswap V3 pool over the TWAP window and then triggers price-sensitive flows such as borrow openings, collateral checks, or liquidations."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[]}
